  "text": "The synchronization of clocks in a distributed network from noisy measurements of their time offsets is another example of synchronization, where the underlying group is the real line R. The eigenvector and semidefinite programming methods for solving an instance of the synchronization problem were originally introduced by Singer in [CITATION_1] in the context of angular synchronization, where one is asked to estimate n unknown angles θ 1 , . . . , θ n ∈ [0, 2π) given m noisy measurements δ ij of their offsets θ i − θ j mod 2π. The difficulty of the problem is amplified on one hand by the amount of noise in the offset measurements, and on the other hand by the fact that m n 2 , i.e., only a very small subset of all possible pairwise offsets are measured. In general, one may consider other groups G (such as SO(d), O(d)) for which there are available noisy measurements g ij of ratios between the group elements g ij = g i g −1 j , g i , g j ∈ G.",
